1
00:00:00,400 --> 00:00:07,120
Losing scalpers trade with lagging indicators 
like RSI and moving averages. Professional  

2
00:00:07,120 --> 00:00:13,840
scalpers read order flow and market microstructure 
with tools that you've probably never even heard  

3
00:00:13,840 --> 00:00:20,880
of. Here are eight scalping techniques 
that separate losers from professionals.

4
00:00:20,880 --> 00:00:26,800
Mark the previous day's high and low, then 
watch how price interacts at those levels.  

5
00:00:26,800 --> 00:00:33,520
This area often works like a magnet, drawing 
attention from both buyers and sellers. You  

6
00:00:33,520 --> 00:00:40,240
want to monitor if price breaks through or bounces 
off, or rejects them. Scalpers keep their eyes on  

7
00:00:40,240 --> 00:00:46,640
these breakouts looking for a quick burst. A 
successful break can lead to short-term buys.  

8
00:00:46,640 --> 00:00:54,080
If the break stalls or fails, they may close out 
fast, expecting a slide back into the day's range.

9
00:00:54,080 --> 00:00:59,360
That same logic applies to the previous 
day's low. If price pushes below that  

10
00:00:59,360 --> 00:01:06,000
point but struggles to go lower, it might 
climb back, sparking quick trades. Volume  

11
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:10,320
flow at these points shows who 
carries more weight on the chart:  

12
00:01:10,320 --> 00:01:16,720
the group ready to push higher or the group 
ready to defend and revert price lower.

13
00:01:16,720 --> 00:01:22,480
For instance, day traders might see it with 
a wider view if volume fails to rise and  

14
00:01:22,480 --> 00:01:28,960
the price breaks. They see that as a weakness 
that could hint at a chance to fade the move,  

15
00:01:28,960 --> 00:01:32,720
expecting a drift back into the 
range. In a bullish setting,  

16
00:01:32,720 --> 00:01:38,960
though, a clear break above the past 
high might signal bigger gains. Again,  

17
00:01:38,960 --> 00:01:45,280
wait for retest of these highs or lows to 
confirm support or resistance. A strong  

18
00:01:45,280 --> 00:01:52,560
surge suggests bigger participants stepping in. 
A weak spike suggests the break might not hold.

19
00:01:52,560 --> 00:01:57,200
Another interesting strategy is to 
mark highs and lows from multiple  

20
00:01:57,200 --> 00:02:02,800
days to see confluence. If many 
past highs cluster in one region,  

21
00:02:02,800 --> 00:02:09,360
that marks a bigger level on the chart. Order 
flow analysis also builds on these zones.  

22
00:02:09,360 --> 00:02:16,160
In a bullish flow, price may seek buy stops 
above a prior high. When price drives higher,  

23
00:02:16,160 --> 00:02:22,480
that might feed more buying interest. In a 
bearish flow, it might head for sell stops below  

24
00:02:22,480 --> 00:02:30,960
a previous low. If momentum keeps running, price 
extends further. If it fails, it can whip back.

25
00:02:30,960 --> 00:02:36,400
Footprint charts split each candlestick 
into two columns of executed orders.  

26
00:02:36,400 --> 00:02:42,160
One column shows the volume on the bid side 
and the other shows the volume on the ask  

27
00:02:42,160 --> 00:02:49,680
side. This view helps you see who might be more 
active at each price level. In a strong rally,  

28
00:02:49,680 --> 00:02:55,520
the footprint can reveal if buyers are 
pushing price upward in a steady way.  

29
00:02:55,520 --> 00:03:01,600
In a strong drop, it can reveal if sellers 
keep hitting the market with large orders.

30
00:03:01,600 --> 00:03:08,000
This method is direct and numeric. A footprint 
chart doesn't rely on a guess about patterns.  

31
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:14,400
It relies on actual trades. Each block of 
traded contracts or shares is visible at  

32
00:03:14,400 --> 00:03:21,200
each step. Imbalances come into play here. 
An imbalance occurs when one side greatly  

33
00:03:21,200 --> 00:03:27,920
exceeds the other at a given price level. On a 
footprint chart, that might appear as a large  

34
00:03:27,920 --> 00:03:34,640
difference between the bid-side volume and the 
ask-side volume. This gap can hint at which side  

35
00:03:34,640 --> 00:03:40,800
is more aggressive. It can also reveal if 
big participants are stepping in with size.

36
00:03:40,800 --> 00:03:47,840
In a fast-moving uptrend, repeated buy imbalances 
can reinforce the bullish pressure. If you see  

37
00:03:47,840 --> 00:03:54,720
repeated sell imbalances, you might guess that 
big participants are forcing price lower. At  

38
00:03:54,720 --> 00:04:00,640
key turning points, footprints might show 
signs of absorption. Absorption means one  

39
00:04:00,640 --> 00:04:06,320
side is absorbing the other side's orders. 
That can appear on the footprint. If you see  

40
00:04:06,320 --> 00:04:13,840
big numbers on both sides but no real progress 
upward in an uptrend, a footprint might reveal  

41
00:04:13,840 --> 00:04:20,080
hidden pockets of supply. If the bars show 
large selling imbalances at certain levels,  

42
00:04:20,080 --> 00:04:27,040
that might stop the move. The idea is to watch 
the actual fight between buyers and sellers.  

43
00:04:27,040 --> 00:04:30,320
The footprint is a lens into the order flow.

44
00:04:30,320 --> 00:04:37,360
At times, the footprint view can show that even in 
a strong uptrend, large sell orders keep popping  

45
00:04:37,360 --> 00:04:44,640
up at certain levels. Price might stall there. If 
the volume on the buy side absorbs those sellers,  

46
00:04:44,640 --> 00:04:51,520
price might break higher anyway. But if large 
sellers hold that line, price might turn. The  

47
00:04:51,520 --> 00:04:58,000
footprint chart helps highlight these battles. 
A normal chart might show a candle with a wick,  

48
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:04,160
but the footprint might show that this wick 
printed huge trades on the left side. That can  

49
00:05:04,160 --> 00:05:11,920
sometimes mean a sudden wave of sellers. For day 
trading or scalping, footprint charts are a must.

50
00:05:11,920 --> 00:05:17,600
Some charts show hidden pivot clusters. 
These clusters happen when three or four  

51
00:05:17,600 --> 00:05:24,640
pivot highs or lows stack near one price. 
I personally like to watch to see if price  

52
00:05:24,640 --> 00:05:30,880
builds a block of these points. Price might 
respect these zones. It might hit that band  

53
00:05:30,880 --> 00:05:37,120
and pause. It might bounce off it or break 
through. These clusters can matter to many  

54
00:05:37,120 --> 00:05:43,360
groups of traders. And I try to keep my chart 
structure simple. If there are three or four  

55
00:05:43,360 --> 00:05:50,320
pivot points in the same neighborhood, that can 
form a hidden cluster. If I group them together,  

56
00:05:50,320 --> 00:05:56,800
I see a stronger band. This can help 
me spot places where price might react.

57
00:05:56,800 --> 00:06:02,960
I treat these clusters like wide support or 
resistance zones. They are not exact single  

58
00:06:02,960 --> 00:06:10,960
lines. They are areas on the chart. Sometimes 
these clusters coincide with pivot points. Many  

59
00:06:10,960 --> 00:06:18,640
day traders and scalpers use daily pivot formulas. 
If a cluster lines up with a pivot calculation,  

60
00:06:18,640 --> 00:06:24,880
that might strengthen the zone further. 
It might bring more eyes onto that spot.  

61
00:06:24,880 --> 00:06:30,000
That can create a self-fulfilling 
effect, at least for a short time.

62
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:36,720
I also look for clusters that might be hidden 
inside candle wicks. The market spikes up or  

63
00:06:36,720 --> 00:06:44,320
down and leaves a wick. That wick might mark a 
pivot high or low. If I see multiple wicks that  

64
00:06:44,320 --> 00:06:50,960
poke into the same area, I might highlight 
that as a cluster. The candle body closes  

65
00:06:50,960 --> 00:06:57,440
might not show the same price, but the wicks 
might. That can still matter to me. If price  

66
00:06:57,440 --> 00:07:04,080
returns there, it can trigger a new burst 
of activity or it might hold as a barrier.

67
00:07:04,080 --> 00:07:10,160
I also consider how wide the band is. If 
the pivots are spread over a big range,  

68
00:07:10,160 --> 00:07:16,080
it might be less precise. If the pivots are 
very close together, the cluster might be  

69
00:07:16,080 --> 00:07:24,160
tighter. Tight clusters can create sharp reversals 
because many orders might be loaded at nearly the  

70
00:07:24,160 --> 00:07:32,080
same price. Wide clusters can lead to choppier 
action because price might drift within that zone.

71
00:07:32,080 --> 00:07:38,400
Some see clusters of pivot highs as zones 
full of potential sell orders. Clusters of  

72
00:07:38,400 --> 00:07:44,720
pivot lows may hold buy orders. That might 
be because each pivot left a memory in the  

73
00:07:44,720 --> 00:07:51,680
market. Some participants may have open orders 
there from before, or they see that zone as a  

74
00:07:51,680 --> 00:08:00,160
logical place to set stops or limit entries. 
This is why these clusters can become magnets.

75
00:08:00,160 --> 00:08:07,040
TPO stands for Time Price Opportunity and is 
a great tool for scalping and day trading.  

76
00:08:07,040 --> 00:08:13,920
A TPO chart displays time at price in a 
letter-based format. These charts break  

77
00:08:13,920 --> 00:08:20,000
down each time frame into letters. Each letter 
aligns with a price level in that time frame.  

78
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:26,400
One advantage of TPO charts is how they 
strip away messy candle wicks. Instead,  

79
00:08:26,400 --> 00:08:30,400
you see a clean layout of 
time spent at each price.

80
00:08:30,400 --> 00:08:35,680
A bar chart might show big upper 
shadows or wide intraday ranges,  

81
00:08:35,680 --> 00:08:43,120
but it can be unclear how much time was spent at 
certain levels. TPO charts reveal that detail.  

82
00:08:43,120 --> 00:08:49,760
If you see 10 letters at one level, that means 10 
distinct time blocks spent some portion of trading  

83
00:08:49,760 --> 00:08:56,800
at that price. That is a direct way to sense 
how the market balanced or tested each zone.

84
00:08:56,800 --> 00:09:01,040
If a big cluster forms around the 
middle of the day, some interpret  

85
00:09:01,040 --> 00:09:06,080
that as a balanced session. When you 
see the cluster push up near the top,  

86
00:09:06,080 --> 00:09:10,720
you might sense that participants 
welcomed higher pricing. If you spot  

87
00:09:10,720 --> 00:09:16,800
a cluster near the bottom, that can mean 
persistent acceptance at lower levels.

88
00:09:16,800 --> 00:09:22,960
A short stack of letters at a certain price 
might show that the market tested that level  

89
00:09:22,960 --> 00:09:29,680
but quickly moved away. That might reflect swift 
rejection. If the price tried to stay there,  

90
00:09:29,680 --> 00:09:34,400
you would see more letters added. 
If you see only one or two letters,  

91
00:09:34,400 --> 00:09:38,880
that can mean the market spent 
just one or two time blocks there.

92
00:09:38,880 --> 00:09:44,800
Some traders place special importance 
on single TPO prints at extremes. That  

93
00:09:44,800 --> 00:09:50,400
single print might highlight a strong 
rejection. Market profile watchers may  

94
00:09:50,400 --> 00:09:56,480
call that a sign that the market poked into 
that territory, found no willingness to trade,  

95
00:09:56,480 --> 00:10:03,680
and reversed. Rejection becomes visible because 
the chart never built a tall column there.

96
00:10:03,680 --> 00:10:09,760
The middle area often becomes the point of 
control, referencing the price level with the most  

97
00:10:09,760 --> 00:10:18,000
TPOs. In many sessions, the distribution might not 
be symmetrical. It could skew higher or it might  

98
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:25,840
skew lower. That tilt can show that either buyers 
or sellers took control for much of the session.

99
00:10:25,840 --> 00:10:32,560
In an active bullish scenario, you might see 
a heavy cluster of letters near the top. That  

100
00:10:32,560 --> 00:10:39,680
can hint the market accepted higher prices, 
finishing near the highs with a strong cluster.  

101
00:10:39,680 --> 00:10:45,040
In a bearish environment, you might 
see a thick cluster near the lows.  

102
00:10:45,040 --> 00:10:49,280
That can mean repeated trading 
activity in that lower region.

103
00:10:49,280 --> 00:10:56,880
People also track the value area in a TPO chart. 
The value area often covers the price range where  

104
00:10:56,880 --> 00:11:04,720
70% of the day's TPO activity took place. 
That area is presumably the day's fair zone.  

105
00:11:04,720 --> 00:11:11,120
Day traders watch the open in relation to the 
prior day's value area. If the market opens  

106
00:11:11,120 --> 00:11:18,160
above it and keeps building letters at higher 
levels, it can reflect bullish acceptance. If  

107
00:11:18,160 --> 00:11:25,760
it drops back into the previous day's value area, 
that might show a failure to sustain new ground.

108
00:11:25,760 --> 00:11:32,800
Combine a trend line with a volume spike 
test to see how price reacts on each retest.  

109
00:11:32,800 --> 00:11:38,880
Draw a steady line through points on your 
chart. Then watch how volume changes each  

110
00:11:38,880 --> 00:11:45,040
time price touches that zone. Here 
we have a rising line under price.  

111
00:11:45,040 --> 00:11:50,800
Suppose price taps that line more than 
once. Track the effort behind each tap.

112
00:11:50,800 --> 00:11:57,200
If volume expands at the contact point but price 
does not break lower, buyers might be holding the  

113
00:11:57,200 --> 00:12:04,960
line. That reveal can guide you to think buyers 
are present despite the test. If price closes  

114
00:12:04,960 --> 00:12:12,480
firm above the line, that hints that buyers 
outweigh sellers, so the uptrend may continue.

115
00:12:12,480 --> 00:12:18,560
On the other hand, imagine volume spikes at 
the trend line as the price breaks. The line  

116
00:12:18,560 --> 00:12:25,040
can become a weaker barrier. A strong 
close beyond it can mark a firm change.  

117
00:12:25,040 --> 00:12:30,880
Sometimes you see a wide bar pushing 
through that line with large activity  

118
00:12:30,880 --> 00:12:37,920
and no bounce on the retest. That scenario 
often signals a real shift. You might see a  

119
00:12:37,920 --> 00:12:45,120
giant volume bar as the final push and price 
continues well below the line. That can warn  

120
00:12:45,120 --> 00:12:51,040
that sellers stepped in aggressively. 
The line no longer stands in their way.

121
00:12:51,040 --> 00:12:58,640
First, test your approach on past charts. Open 
a chart and draw your rising or declining line.  

122
00:12:58,640 --> 00:13:04,560
Then, wait for price to drift there. When 
it does, watch the volume level. If volume  

123
00:13:04,560 --> 00:13:11,360
exceeds the average by a visible margin, see how 
the candle closes. Does it close well above the  

124
00:13:11,360 --> 00:13:18,240
trend line or below it? That single data point 
can speak volumes about the market intent.

125
00:13:18,240 --> 00:13:26,080
Watch for sideways drifting near the line. If 
price stalls near that line and volume bars climb,  

126
00:13:26,080 --> 00:13:32,480
that might suggest big players are building 
positions. Price might then explode above  

127
00:13:32,480 --> 00:13:40,000
or below. A strong breakout with a wide range 
bar plus large activity can confirm the path.  

128
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:46,080
A breakout with low volume will often fade. 
Observing the spike helps you see if big  

129
00:13:46,080 --> 00:13:54,240
participation is present. That is the advantage 
of combining a trend line with volume spike tests.

130
00:13:54,240 --> 00:14:01,440
Examining each bar's range is a simple way to 
see if price might break free or stay quiet. The  

131
00:14:01,440 --> 00:14:08,000
gap between the bar's high and low reflects 
market energy. A bar's high reveals how far  

132
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:15,840
buyers try to push. A bar's low shows how far 
sellers try to push in that same period. That  

133
00:14:15,840 --> 00:14:22,080
difference in height, known as the range, 
can show if the market is slow or alive.

134
00:14:22,080 --> 00:14:28,880
A big range can hint that traders are pushing 
and pulling with greater force. A small range  

135
00:14:28,880 --> 00:14:36,400
can point to caution or waiting. This practice is 
called range analysis and it starts with reading  

136
00:14:36,400 --> 00:14:43,680
each bar in a straightforward way. It does not 
require fancy tools. A day trader looks at the  

137
00:14:43,680 --> 00:14:51,520
bar on the chart, notes the distance from high to 
low, and compares it to prior bars. If the new bar  

138
00:14:51,520 --> 00:14:58,800
towers over the one before it, that can be a sign 
of more volatility. If the new bar is smaller,  

139
00:14:58,800 --> 00:15:05,600
that can be a sign of reduced action. This is 
a direct and practical way to gain insight.

140
00:15:05,600 --> 00:15:10,720
Range expansions can show that something 
has changed. A large bar might mean that  

141
00:15:10,720 --> 00:15:16,720
many players jumped in during that period. 
Traders holding positions could have strong  

142
00:15:16,720 --> 00:15:23,680
opinions on direction. That strong opinion can 
create a surge. When price covers more ground,  

143
00:15:23,680 --> 00:15:28,880
it can catch some off guard. Some might 
see the big bar and believe the market is  

144
00:15:28,880 --> 00:15:34,560
on the move. Others might step aside, 
not wanting to fight that momentum.

145
00:15:34,560 --> 00:15:39,920
Contraction is the opposite. When bars 
get smaller, it might show that traders  

146
00:15:39,920 --> 00:15:45,520
are waiting. They might not see a clear 
path. The highs are not too high. The lows  

147
00:15:45,520 --> 00:15:52,880
are not too low. That can create a cluster of 
narrow bars, each one marking a slim distance  

148
00:15:52,880 --> 00:15:59,840
between high and low. Some traders anticipate 
a breakout from such quiet stages. They keep  

149
00:15:59,840 --> 00:16:06,800
watching for that first big bar that bursts 
in one direction. That bar can bring energy,  

150
00:16:06,800 --> 00:16:13,280
hooking new orders into the market. Others 
remain cautious, unsure if the quiet phase  

151
00:16:13,280 --> 00:16:20,720
will continue. Sometimes the quiet phase drags 
on, frustrating those who wait for a spark.

152
00:16:20,720 --> 00:16:26,560
Seeing expansions or contractions in 
the bar range helps judge market tempo.  

153
00:16:26,560 --> 00:16:32,400
It shows if the market is active or calm. 
This direct reading helps keep the focus  

154
00:16:32,400 --> 00:16:38,880
on price. Of course, you must pair it with 
volume data. You want to see if the wide bar  

155
00:16:38,880 --> 00:16:44,800
also had high volume. That suggests 
strong commitment from big players.

156
00:16:44,800 --> 00:16:51,440
Candle close location value shows how each 
bar finishes relative to its high-low range.  

157
00:16:51,440 --> 00:16:56,880
If a candle closes near its high, buyers 
kept pushing until the end of that time  

158
00:16:56,880 --> 00:17:02,560
frame. If a candle closes near the low, 
it shows larger selling pressure toward  

159
00:17:02,560 --> 00:17:08,320
that bar's finish. A close around the 
midpoint marks a balance between buyers  

160
00:17:08,320 --> 00:17:16,240
and sellers. Day traders watch these closes to 
see who seems stronger over a series of bars.

161
00:17:16,240 --> 00:17:22,560
If many bars close near their highs, it can 
hint that buyers are consistently winning.  

162
00:17:22,560 --> 00:17:29,600
In an uptrend, a streak of bars that finish 
high suggests strong interest at each step.  

163
00:17:29,600 --> 00:17:36,960
If a bar suddenly closes near its low after 
that streak, it may point to a shift in mood.

164
00:17:36,960 --> 00:17:44,400
This 5-minute chart shows consecutive closes near 
the top. That can mean buyers are active on each  

165
00:17:44,400 --> 00:17:52,160
bar's final trades. If the next bar closes deep 
in the range, watch if buyers step aside. If that  

166
00:17:52,160 --> 00:18:00,960
low close coincides with wider ranges or bigger 
candles, it might reveal a sudden wave of selling.

167
00:18:00,960 --> 00:18:07,520
Candle close location also helps you detect 
subtle shifts. Suppose a market moves upward  

168
00:18:07,520 --> 00:18:13,440
but the candles start closing near their 
midpoints, creating shadows on top. You  

169
00:18:13,440 --> 00:18:19,360
might guess that sellers are active even 
if price is still climbing. Over time,  

170
00:18:19,360 --> 00:18:26,560
those repeated mid-range closes could foreshadow 
a stall. On the flip side, a market in a downtrend  

171
00:18:26,560 --> 00:18:33,040
that begins closing near the high of each 
bar might show stronger buying than before.

172
00:18:33,040 --> 00:18:38,640
Traders sometimes calculate an average 
candle close location over a set of bars.  

173
00:18:38,640 --> 00:18:44,880
If a candle closes near its high, its 
value is one. If it closes near its low,  

174
00:18:44,880 --> 00:18:52,240
its value is zero. If it closes in the 
middle, it has a value of 0.5. Then you  

175
00:18:52,240 --> 00:18:59,760
consider the average value over a set of bars. 
If that average stays near 0.8, for example,  

176
00:18:59,760 --> 00:19:07,440
bullish pressure is steady. If it oscillates 
around 0.5, the market looks indecisive. A  

177
00:19:07,440 --> 00:19:16,320
swift drop toward 0.1 can point to a big change in 
tone. Candle close location is straightforward and  

178
00:19:16,320 --> 00:19:25,680
thrives on raw price action. That direct view can 
help you sense if momentum is building or fading.

179
00:19:25,680 --> 00:19:32,880
Identify a measured move to see how price might 
extend in a trend. Picture a market that rises a  

180
00:19:32,880 --> 00:19:38,640
certain distance, then pulls back, and then 
drives higher again. That distance from the  

181
00:19:38,640 --> 00:19:45,280
first surge often helps you estimate how far 
the next wave might go. You take the size of  

182
00:19:45,280 --> 00:19:52,240
the first move and project it above the pullback. 
This is a measured move, a quick way to guess a  

183
00:19:52,240 --> 00:19:58,000
possible target. If the market meets that 
target and stalls, that might confirm the  

184
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:04,960
measured move idea. If the market blasts past 
the target, that might reveal extra strength.

185
00:20:04,960 --> 00:20:13,600
Imagine a clean uptrend. Price rallies 100 pips 
from a swing low. Then it retraces about 50 pips,  

186
00:20:13,600 --> 00:20:22,000
forming a short pause. Now price moves up again. 
Some traders measure that first wave and plot that  

187
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:28,320
same distance from the swing low of the pullback. 
That new level becomes a reference. They watch  

188
00:20:28,320 --> 00:20:35,600
if price hits it or not. This approach feels 
basic, but it can help you map out expectations.  

189
00:20:35,600 --> 00:20:42,000
You look for symmetrical movement in a trending 
environment. If a market makes a series of waves  

190
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:48,880
that mirror each other in size, that might confirm 
the trend has a steady rhythm. If you see multiple  

191
00:20:48,880 --> 00:20:55,280
measured moves that keep playing out, you get a 
sense that the trend is healthy and consistent.

192
00:20:55,280 --> 00:21:01,360
Of course, markets don't always honor the 
symmetrical moves precisely. You might see  

193
00:21:01,360 --> 00:21:08,480
it come close, then fade, or you might see it 
power right through. Measured moves aim to give  

194
00:21:08,480 --> 00:21:14,320
you a ballpark estimate, not an absolute 
rule. But this concept can also help you  

195
00:21:14,320 --> 00:21:20,880
with risk assessment and with your targets. 
This is a simple chart geometry approach. You  

196
00:21:20,880 --> 00:21:27,040
measure a prior leg and replicate it. You 
see if the market respects that geometry.

197
00:21:27,040 --> 00:21:32,720
So use symmetrical moves to project possible 
targets and then interpret if the market  

198
00:21:32,720 --> 00:21:38,800
exceeds or falls short of that measure. 
If it overshoots, it might be a sign of  

199
00:21:38,800 --> 00:21:45,600
strong momentum. If it undershoots, it might 
warn that momentum is weaker than before.

200
00:21:45,600 --> 00:21:50,000
And if you're ready to fit this 
into a full A to Z trading system,  

201
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:57,840
that's what our academy is for. 
